lfer-spheres5e.universal.kXl7jsRFJ0z3MrnV]{Extreme Opportunistic}</li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.universal.cNpt06pu2KH7SPec]{Extreme Reach}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.universal.mFeNfZxGpL6HWG70]{Extreme Striking}</p></li></ul>","chat":"","unidentified":""},"source":"Spheres of Power","activation":{"type":"","cost":null,"condition":""},"duration":{"value":"","units":""},"cover":null,"target":{"value":null,"width":null,"units":"","type":""},"range":{"value":null,"long":null,"units":""},"uses":{"value":null,"max":"","per":null,"recovery":""},"consume":{"type":"","target":null,"amount":null},"ability":"","actionType":"","attackBonus":"","chatFlavor":"","critical":{"threshold":null,"damage":""},"damage":{"parts":[],"versatile":""},"formula":"","save":{"ability":"","dc":null,"scaling":"spell"},"type":{"value":"","subtype":""},"requirements":"","recharge":{"value":null,"charged":false}},"img":"icons/magic/light/explosion-glow-spiral-teal.webp","effects":[],"ownership":{"default":0,"jvc9MjSXj7pOw4bp":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Actor.6TytIci8hugkzf0S.Item.Rm7MRuNF7za7fCde"}},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.1.5","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1685604811910,"modifiedTime":1685611987078,"lastModifiedBy":"jvc9MjSXj7pOw4bp"},"folder":null,"sort":0,"_id":"jgO3ox7VXQZVNttm"}
{"name":"Illusion Sphere","type":"feat","system":{"description":{"value":"<p>You can craft images and impressions of things that arenâ€™t there.</p><h3><span><strong>Using Illusions</strong></span></h3><p>Illusions can be particularly difficult for players and Game Masters, because most of their power comes from how they affect the narrative; illusions by their very nature mislead, and while using illusions against players can be done easily (a Game Master can simply tell their players â€˜you see a wallâ€™ without telling them it is an illusion, then see how they behave), a Game Master is expected to both know when the players are using illusions, as well as control NPCs who very well might not know. The Illusions sphere is written with the following expectations and guidelines for how @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figments} work in practice, and these guidelines should help players and Game Masters agree on their expectations.</p><h4 id=\"toc1\"><span><strong>Belief vs Disbelief</strong></span></h4><p>In a world of magic, unless a creature knows they are dealing with an illusionist, they will not automatically doubt anything they see; a guard familiar with a city streets might know that an illusionary wall wasnâ€™t dividing the street yesterday, but they wonâ€™t automatically know it is an illusion; it very well might be a real wall summoned by a Creation caster instead. Likewise, a caster who appears to summon monsters to aid in a fight might be creating illusions, or summoning actual monsters.</p><p>Thus, even if an NPC has a reason to be suspicious of an illusion, they will need to at least use an action to attempt to disbelieve an illusionary wall before charging through it, or spend an action attacking an illusionary creature to see their attack go through it (or, if the illusion is being actively guided by the illusionist or possesses the @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.ErCjuJJn3i0ygoaJ]{Intelligent Illusions} talent, spend a few rounds attacking it before they become suspicious that the illusion â€˜somehowâ€™ keeps dodging every attack). It is only if they know they are facing an illusionist (such as by having seen through their earlier illusions) that they might charge through the wall without waiting to examine it or ignore the creatures summoned to attack it, but even then they risk a clever magic user who places illusions the first time, then summons real walls and creatures the second time when the guards are primed to ignore them.</p><h4 id=\"toc2\"><span><strong>Covering Objects with Figments</strong></span></h4><p>While the @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.JWtKAjGVFd2g9kw9]{Illusionary Disguise} talent can allow you to change the appearance of a creature or object, it is also possible to place a @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figment} on top of something to hide it. For example, you could place a @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figment} on top of a creature to give the impression it is transforming into a monster, or hide a door behind a @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figment} of a rock. These @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figments}, however, do not move with the creature or object they are placed over (they must be moved as an action by the caster), and also have the chance to be disbelieved and therefore turn transparent once uncovered.</p><h4 id=\"toc3\"><span><strong>Illusionary Cover</strong></span></h4><p>While summoning a @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figment} of a wall might discourage someone from trying to attack you through it, the cover is not real, and so therefore does not actually provide cover if the target attempts to attack. If the attack succeeds, the attacker will have seen their attack pass through the illusion and will know the cover is fake.</p><h4 id=\"toc4\"><span><strong>Automatic Disbelief</strong></span></h4><p>Remember that once a target has seen proof that a @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figment} is illusionary (for example, a guard shoots an arrow through an illusionary wall, or a guard sees the PCs enter the illusion of a rock, or sees ranged attacks coming from inside a rock), they automatically disbelieve the @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figment}, and therefore automatically can see through it. A creature does not need to be next to an illusion to examine it, interact with it (throwing or firing ranged weapons can do so), or see something pass through it.</p><h4 id=\"toc5\"><span><strong>Alternative Uses</strong></span></h4><p>Illusions can be used in ways not tied to fooling someone. You could use an audible illusion to throw your voice and whisper messages at a distance. You could use visible illusions to show someone the image of a person or map you have seen.</p><p>An @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.JWtKAjGVFd2g9kw9]{Illusionary Disguise} with @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.w0uruW7YzHNEANaA]{Greater Illusion} could be used to give advantage on a check made with cooking utensils (in essence, covering up any mistakes in the cooking with pleasant smells and tastes), or a @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figment} could be used to make a Performance check to entertain.</p><hr /><p>When you first gain the Illusion sphere, you gain the following abilities:</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{Figment} and @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.jTmvnj5tbm8mRAFD]{Glamer}</p><hr /><p><strong>Glamer Talents</strong></p><ul><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b8GiXxsni5uTmLvq]{Decoy (glamer)}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.JWtKAjGVFd2g9kw9]{Illusionary Disguise (glamer)}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.AV0NaE0WWB3IgbAH]{Obscure (glamer)}</p></li></ul><hr /><p><strong>Sensory Talents</strong></p><ul><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.w0uruW7YzHNEANaA]{Greater Illusions (sensory)}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.fSPwuGZDlNgEqvQT]{Veiled Illusions (sensory)}</p></li></ul><hr /><p><strong>Other Talents</strong></p><ul><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.wTn9TBv4zWrYMewS]{Illusionary Obstruction}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.WQFEsG1PPa3ncy5a]{Complex Illusions}</p></li><li>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.XutHskWM3rzgHqAK]{Control Figment}</li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.O360V6fx9efGruaw]{Illusionary Terrain}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.FviiIS09r0j3f3nA]{Insistent Illusions}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.9PMsjiFA3iQI5uDN]{Potent Illusions}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.PJp25hTavc57wRO4]{Programmed Illusion}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.TEflC8o1F2xAiBkR]{Selective Illusions}</p></li></ul><hr /><p><strong>Advanced Talents</strong></p><ul><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.ErCjuJJn3i0ygoaJ]{Intelligent Illusions (sensory)}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.Ue1SKqUBVmFNJ3CF]{Mirage}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.PfQPf43D65fMuDop]{Permanent Illusion}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.HvLULNB9GQ2ApmgH]{Shadow Infusion}</p></li></ul><hr /><p><strong>Variants</strong></p><ul><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.3gzJ3PhKxy9osrS1]{Alternative Illusions}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.LCizKfB4RncVO67z]{Imageless}</p></li></ul><hr /><p><strong>(Optional) Figment Talents</strong></p><p>By design, illusions are open-ended magical abilities; often, the difference between an effective illusionist and an ineffective illusionist is how the player and GM interact when deciding how NPCs react to those illusions. This anguish sometimes results in house rules where players and GMs agree to place heavy restrictions on the use of illusion magic.</p><p>The following talents replace the default @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figment} power with a series of â€˜<strong>figment</strong> talentsâ€™. With these talents, the nature of an illusion doesnâ€™t matter; a player doesnâ€™t need to decide if they are going to summon the image of a rock or a soldier or determine how â€˜convincingâ€™ something is, instead they simply need to decide what effect they want to accomplish and see if they have the appropriate <strong>(figment)</strong> talent. Mechanics of disbelief generally do not apply to a <strong>(figment)</strong> talent, and what senses a creature possesses does not determine if they are affected.</p><p>If using this variant, the @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{figment} power is replaced by @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.mkyArd580qQASaQO]{Figment (Optional)}, and creatures gaining the Illusion sphere can choose either a <strong>(glamer)</strong> or <strong>(figment)</strong> talent as a bonus talent when they gain the sphere. If the GM chooses, both the @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{base figment} power and <strong>(figment)</strong> talents might even be included in the same game, although players must choose which they begin with, and spend a talent to gain either a <strong>(figment)</strong> talent or the @UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.b1XgEOuW7gWwNPPR]{base figment} ability later if they desire both.</p><hr /><p><strong>Figment Talents</strong></p><ul><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.oHETtvnwTHhpeWV0]{Illusionary Combatants (figment)}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.YYPpgiUYFkEXIGgz]{Illusionary Cover (figment)}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Compendium.wolfer-spheres5e.illusion.YfrJf